9,"createdAt":1334017085000,"spoilerStatus":false,"lastRevisionAt":1334607729000,"text":"Last night I burned through the remaining 200 pages of the book To Selena, With Love written by Chris Perez. It might be because I grew up listening to her music, because I vaguely remember seeing her all over Telemundo when I was at my grandmothers house, or because I remember seeing the movie based on her life in theaters (I was very young), but while finishing this book last night, I struggled to keep it together and eventually I cried over the loss of this amazing woman.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eToday would have been Selena Quintanilla’s 41st birthday had she not been shot and killed on March 31st, 1995.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eFor those of you who may not know of her, Selena was a Tejano superstar singer from Corpus Christi, Texas who grew up on the road with her family/band Los Dinos which was managed by her father, Abraham Quintanilla. She was known for many hit songs, among them: “Como La Flor”, “Bidi Bidi Bom Bom”, “Amor Porhibido” and my personal favorite, her cover of “Tu Solo Tu”. She was also infamous for her eccentric costumes, her winning smile and her generous actions.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThe book, written by her lead Guitarist who would later become her husband, is a remarkable tell-all account of the relationship between Quintanilla and Perez, dating back to their first encounter with one another when they flew back from a gig in Alcapulco, to the very last time he saw his beloved wife.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eIf you have seen the movie Selena (1997) then you are only somewhat familiar with her career and her personal life because this book delves into the singers persona through personal accounts so well that only after reading it can you truly see who the real Selena was.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI loved the honesty that Perez filled the pages of this book with. It was as if he was telling me these stories to my face. He could describe Selena’s voice, body and character so accurately and it was easy to visualize the stories within this book. You understood what Perez was trying to emphasize, what he really wanted people to take from this book. You felt his nervousness and frustration towards Abraham at the start of Chris and Selena’s, at the time, secret relationship. You saw the words he used to describe his love for Selena practically burning with passion on the page. You laughed out loud when he told stories of their adventures on motorcylcles or how they managed to keep 5 dogs, a snake, a mouse and an entire aquarium in their home without losing it. And you felt the extreme emptiness he felt after her untimely death so sharply that your heart ached. The fact that after 17 years he was able to recount his precious memories and publish them for her fans, and for himself, says a lot about him and I respect that.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThis book gave me a greater understanding of who Selena was. While reading these 304 pages she transformed from my vision of her as just a Tejano music icon into an actual person. At times I even heard her laughter through the pages, a sound that I can only imagine to be as beautiful and passionate as her voice.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI recommend this book to all fans of Selena, to music lovers, to Mexican-Americans such as myself, or anyone interested in reading about a beautiful woman inside and out whos life and talent was taken away from us way too soon. Selena was an extremely talented woman who I now know to be an extremely loving, caring and inspiring person who, had she been allowed more time on this Earth, absolutely would have revolutionized the music industry and the world more than she already has.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eHappy Birthday Selena, we are Dreaming of You.","rating":5,"shelving":{"__typename":"Shelving","shelf":{"__typename":"Shelf","name":"read","webUrl":"https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/7668847?shel